title: For Sale/Trade:  Camillus M-9 Military Bayonet CAM1A1
postcontent:
XM8 Bayonet CAM-1A1
Production Sample - Prototype
AW-CAM1A

Designed for the 21st Century by Bob Terzuola, the Camillus 1A1 Bayonet was designed as the Camillus Cutlery entry for the XM8/Army/Marine Corp Bayonet upgrade project.

This bayonet meets all of the US Government specifications & design requirements, and then some.

The handle is dual overmolded polymer with a soft texture and multiple gripping surfaces. It is comfortable in both forward and reverse grips. The color is Coyote Brown with Loam Green grip panels on each side. An index finger notch has been incorporated for additional grip security in wet or slippery situations.

The blade measures 7.375" and is made from the super rugged Camillus 0170-6C carbon steel. lt features a near full length double edge, with 2" of serrations for extra cutting power on the primary edge. The double edge allows the weilder to cut in both directions while in combat, unlike the current single edge of the M9 bayonet.

The sheath is just as remarkable; featuring the same duo molded technology and a noise reduction panel on the front. Reversable for right or left hand use, the sheath also features a built in sharpening hone for field maintenance of the knife's cutting edge. The polymer sheath also houses the removable wire cutters with two different types of cutters, one sheer type cuts razor ribbon, the other cuts chain-link or barbed wire, and it has a spade type screw driver on the end. A quick release Bianchi clip attaches the sheath to standard military web belts, and the entire system can quickly be detached using the integral side release buckle.

The 1A1 XM8 Bayonet will fit all current standard US Military bayonet mounting hardware.

General Specifications
Blade Length:: 7.375" (partially serrated)
Overall Length:: 12.5"
Blade Steel:: 0170-6C
Handle Material:: Polymer
Sheath:: Polymer
Weight: 13oz

Box, documents and a silicone cloth are all present with this knife.
This knife is very hard to find it this configuration and then as a complete set. The blade is Crazy sharp, it would cut the arm off a Zombie like a hot knife through butter!

Get it as a collector piece, or for the coming Zombie Apocalypse!

AR15 A3 Complete upper assembly with 24 inch Stainless Bull barrel and A3 Upper receiver. This 5.56mm caliber barrel is 24 inches long, and features an 11 degree target crown for muzzle protection. It sports a full length, aluminum alloy handguard. This hand guard is knurled for a positive grip, hardcoat anodized for long life and scratch resistance, and completely free floats the barrel, enhancing accuracy and dissipating heat.  The barrel is machined from 416 R, re-sulpherized, gun quality stainless steel, and hardened to a Rockwell C of 28 to 32 for extremely long life, heat dissipation, and complete corrosion resistance. The 24 inch barrel gives a higher velocity, smaller standard deviation in velocity between shots, and greater accuracy than shorter barrels. All external steel parts are manganese phosphate finished for long lasting good looks and corrosion protection. The barrel is a BULL contour ( .950 diameter under the handguard and .935 diameter under the front sight base) for optimum accuracy The barrel is button rifled with 6 grooves, right hand, 1 / 9 twist. The barrel is mounted on a FORGED A3 upper receiver with built in Mil-spec M1913 Picatinny accessory rail, with the correct rail numbers engraved.

This assembly is ready to be pinned to any AR-15 mil-spec lower receiver and fired.

Also included is a Barska variable high power scope. It ranges from 6.5x-20x with a 50mm objective and pictured bi-pod.

Bi-pod is a UTG.

Barrel was broke in by firing 1 shot and cleaning. Doing this 10 times....then did 10 round shots and cleaned after every tenth round for a total of 110 shots to complete break-in. everything gets cleaned after being shot. Assembly has approx. 600 rounds through it....so its basically new.....

The only mod I have done to this is the mounting of the bi-pod. It was designed to mount picatinny style on the gas block, but that kinda defeats the purpose of a free floated barrel! Instead it is bolted to the underside of the forgrip as seen in pic.

title: For Sale:  AMT Back Up .380 DAO w/holster and extras!
postcontent:
Outstanding double action CCW pistol ... delivers six hollowpoints as fast as you can pull the trigger! No fumbling with a safety or racking the slide. A few handling marks but no scratches or banged-up roll pins. Great condition overall. Grips fine (no cracks or chips), barrel excellent. Forget about plastic guide rods and polymer frames ... these old AMTs are built like tanks. All bead-blasted stainless steel, weighs 21 oz. loaded (5+1). Just enough weight to reduce the felt recoil found in some pocket pistols.

Shoots anything you put in it, not just the high-dollar ammo. I've shot PMC, Blazer, Federal, Fiocchi, brass case, steel case, FMJ, JHP with no issues. One time ... once ... I bought some Tula ammo at WalMart that had a couple of misfires so I tried it in one of my other guns and 11/50 had bad primers. Not the pistol's fault.

BONUS CD: Owner's manual and takedown guide, exploded parts diagram, spec sheets and a 1993 magazine article (that's about the age of this pistol, near as I can determine). Auction price also includes a new holster (bought last week) with rubberized strip that won't move around in your pocket.



Transfers between private parties do not require an FFL or any ATF paperwork but I will need a photocopy of a GDL and/or GFL for my logbook as I am a licensed collector. Feel free to email questions. I prefer to sell outright but I'm always interested in hearing what someone has to trade. Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale:  Inside Waistband Holster - Custom
postcontent:
Another of my favorite IWB designs, this one helps with carrying a gun with a longer grip.  Pictured is my SR9C, which came with a full-size 17 rd. mag (not pictured).  It is tricky to conceal in other holsters I've made, but by placing the loop behind the actual holster the pressure of the belt turns the grip toward the wearer's back.  This diminishes the bulge, and I have heard of people concealing full-size 1911's and Python-sized revolvers in similar rigs.  For larger weapons than my SR9C the price may go up depending on how much more leather and stitching is involved.

Turnaround time is usually about two weeks with me, but I will set three as the maximum since I am a teacher and I'm often quite busy.

title: For Trade:  Original Pheasant Art Circa 1790 for Handgun
postcontent:
You are looking at a rare piece of history here (Pheasant Shooting). This is a 1790 Brittish Aquatint that has three artist's combined works in one. The original piece was painted by George Morland English Painter (1763-1804) with permission it was Etched by Thomas Rowlandson English Painter and Caricaturist (1756-1827) and Aquatinted by Samuel Alken Sr. a Brittish Sporting Artist (1756-1815). 

This was issued as a Sporting Series in 1790 and published by J. Harris and T. Merle. This was acertained by Ralph Richardson's Chronological Catalogue of Etchings and Engravings showing their years of publication (all were published in London). Reference:

http://www.sterlingtimes.org/morland_catalogue2.htm

The above link could also help reflect its value as well.

The artwork is in excellent condition for its age, the colors are period and the paper type period to its age. The piece is framed and matted and ready for display. On the right side there is a slight water stain, this could be extracted or touched up with a professional restoration, however it is not in the main body of the artwork. At the bottom left is G. Morland and T. Rowlandson's credentials and on the lower right is S. Alken's credentials with the date of 1790.

This is a period piece that does not come up for sale often, it is an original and not any type of reproduction. I have no knowledge of art and only inherited this piece and only passing on the research that I have obtained. Please research online or at a local art museum for details. I am told in an auction setting (art type) this piece should sell between 1700 - 2500 USD

Please see photos for quality, condition, size, colors, etc... Thanks so much for your time! For additional photos please email me.
